description: From Middle English webbe, from Old English webb, from Proto-Germanic *wabją, from Proto-Indo-European *webʰ- (“weave”).

entries.meaning: The silken structure which a spider builds using silk secreted from the spinnerets at the caudal tip of its abdomen; a spiderweb.
examples: The sunlight glistened in the dew on the web.

entries.meaning: (by extension) Any interconnected set of persons, places, or things, which, when diagrammed, resembles a spider's web.
(baseball) The part of a baseball mitt between the forefinger and thumb, the webbing.
examples: He caught the ball in the web.

entries.meaning: A latticed or woven structure.
examples: The gazebo’s roof was a web made of thin strips of wood.

entries.meaning: (usually with "spin", "weave", or similar verbs) A tall tale with more complexity than a myth or legend.
examples: Careful—she knows how to spin a good web, but don't lean too hard on what she says.

entries.meaning: A plot or scheme.
The interconnection between flanges in structural members, increasing the effective lever arm and so the load capacity of the member.
(rail transport) The thinner vertical section of a railway rail between the top (head) and bottom (foot) of the rail.
A fold of tissue connecting the toes of certain birds, or of other animals.
The series of barbs implanted on each side of the shaft of a feather, whether stiff and united together by barbules, as in ordinary feathers, or soft and separate, as in downy feathers.
(manufacturing) A continuous strip of material carried by rollers during processing.
(lithography) A long sheet of paper which is fed from a roll into a printing press, as opposed to individual sheets of paper.
(dated) A band of webbing used to regulate the extension of the hood of a carriage.

definitionGroups.group: A thin metal sheet, plate, or strip, as of lead.

entries.meaning: The blade of a sword.
The blade of a saw.
The thin, sharp part of a colter.
The bit of a key.
(dated, US, radio, television) A major broadcasting network.
examples: […]  the first big move toward a contract for television performers was made Friday (20) when the webs agreed to pay them according to the length of the show.  […]  Altho the major TV webs — NBC and CBS — may fall in line soon, an agreement may possibly be held up by the opposition of DuMont  […]

entries.meaning: (architecture) A section of a groin vault, separated by ribs.
(medicine, archaic) A cataract of the eye.
examples: Synonyms: pin and web, web and pin

verbs.description: web (third-person singular simple present webs, present participle webbing, simple past and past participle webbed)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To construct or form a web.
(transitive) To cover with a web or network.
(transitive) To ensnare or entangle.
(transitive) To provide with a web.
(transitive, obsolete) To weave.
